<setup>

  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="4" to="8" step="2"/>  
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="40" to="50" step="5"/>  
  <selectFromSequence name="d" from="0.25" to="0.5" step="0.25"/>  
  
  <function name="v">$b - $a*x</function> 
  <number name="L6">$d * ($$v(0) + $$v($d) + $$v(2*$d) + $$v(3*$d) + $$v(4*$d) + $$v(5*$d))</number>
  <number name="R6">$d * ($$v($d) + $$v(2*$d) + $$v(3*$d) + $$v(4*$d) + $$v(5*$d) + $$v(6*$d))</number>
  <number name="T6">($L6 + $R6)/2</number>

</setup>

  <p>
    Let <m>r(t)</m> represent the rate at which water is draining from a large tank (measured in liters per minute) at time <m>t</m> in minutes.  The following table shows some of the values of <m>v(t)</m>.
  </p>

      <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <row bottom="minor" halign="center">
          <cell><m>t</m></cell>
          <cell><m>0</m></cell>
          <cell><m>$d</m></cell>
          <cell><m><math simplify>2*$d</math></m></cell>
          <cell><m><math simplify>3*$d</math></m></cell> 
          <cell><m><math simplify>4*$d</math></m></cell>  
          <cell><m><math simplify>5*$d</math></m></cell> 
          <cell><m><math simplify>6*$d</math></m></cell>   
        </row>
        <row halign="center">
          <cell><m>r(t)</m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(0)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v($d)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(2*$d)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(3*$d)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(4*$d)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(5*$d)</number></m></cell>
          <cell><m><number displayDecimals="2">$$v(6*$d)</number></m></cell>
        </row>
      </tabular>

<p>
  We are going to use Riemann sums with <m><math simplify>$a/2</math></m> subintervals to estimate the area under the positive rate function <m>r(t)</m> on the interval <m>[0,<math simplify>6*$d</math>]</m>.  
</p>  

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>

      <p>
        For this data, fill in the following blanks to identify the values of <m>\Delta t</m> and <m>t_i</m> for <m>i = 0</m> to <m>i = 6</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>\Delta t = </m><answer>$d</answer>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>t_0 = </m><answer>0</answer>, <m>t_1 = </m><answer>$d</answer>, <m>t_2 = </m><answer>2*$d</answer>, 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>t_3 = </m><answer>3*$d</answer>, <m>t_4 = </m><answer>4*$d</answer>, <m>t_5 = </m><answer>5*$d</answer>, <m>t_6 = </m><answer>6*$d</answer> 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the value of the left Riemann sum with <m>6</m> subintervals. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>L_6 = </m><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute> $L6</answer>
      </p>
    </li> 
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the value of the right Riemann sum with <m>6</m> subintervals. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>R_6 = </m><answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute> $R6</answer>
      </p>
    </li>      
    <li>
      <p>
        Complete the following sentences to explain the meaning of the Riemann sums you found in (b) and (c).
      </p>  
      <p>
        Since the units on <m>r(t)</m> are <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>liters</choice>
          <choice credit="1">liters per minute</choice>
          <choice>minutes</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer> and the units on <m>\Delta t</m> are <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>liters</choice>
          <choice>liters per minute</choice>
          <choice credit="1">minutes</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, when we compute a product such as <m>r(t_2) \cdot \Delta t</m> in a Riemann sum, the units on <m>r(t_2) \cdot \Delta t</m> are
        <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="1">liters</choice>
          <choice>liters per minute</choice>
          <choice>minutes</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>.  This means that each Riemann sum estimates the <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="1">total water that drained from the tank on <m>[0, <math simplify>6*$d</math>]</m></choice>
          <choice>time it took the tank to drain <math simplify>6*$d</math> liters</choice>
          <choice credit="1">average rate the tank is draining on <m>[0, <math simplify>6*$d</math></m></choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, and that a good overall estimate of that quantity is the average of <m>L_6</m> and <m>R_6</m>, which is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute>$T6</answer> liters.
      </p>  
    </li>  
  </ol>  
</p>
